End Function


Binary Search Tree Pseudocode

The BST keeps courses in sorted order automatically.

Load Courses:


Function loadCoursesTree(tree, fileName)

    Read file and store courses

    Validate prerequisites

    Insert each course into tree

End Function


Insert:
Function insertCourseTree(tree, course)

    If root empty
        Set root
        Return

    Move through tree

        If smaller → go left
        If larger → go right

        Insert when empty spot found

End Function


Search:
Function searchCourseTree(tree, courseNumber)

    Start at root

    While node exists
        If match
            Print info
            Return
        If smaller → go left
        Else → go right

    Print not found

End Function


Print All (Sorted):
Function printInOrder(node)

    If empty return

    Traverse left
    Print node
    Traverse right

End Function

Vector	O(n²)	O(n)
Hash Table	O(n²) worst case	O(n)
BST	O(n²) worst case	O(n)

Explanation:

The vector takes longer because it scans lists multiple times, especially when checking prerequisites. The hash table is usually fast, but in the worst case collisions slow it down. The binary search tree can also slow down if it becomes unbalanced, but it performs well in most cases.


Advantages and Disadvantages
Vector:

The vector is easy to use and simple to understand. It works well for smaller datasets. The downside is that searching is slow and sorting has to be done manually.


Hash Table:

The hash table is very fast for searching, which is helpful when looking up courses. However, it does not keep data sorted, so extra work is needed to print courses in order.


Binary Search Tree:

The BST is the best for this project because it keeps data sorted automatically. That makes printing all courses much easier. The only downside is that it can become slower if the tree is not balanced.


Recommendation:

Out of the three options, the binary search tree is the best choice. It handles searching well and prints courses in sorted order without needing extra steps. Even though it can slow down in the worst case, it still fits the requirements of this program better than the vector or hash table.
